com.excelsior.util

Class Nullable<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.excelsior.util.Nullable<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of value

    public final class Nullable<T>
extends java.lang.Object
    A container object which may or may not contain a non-null value. If the value is present isPresent() returns true. If no value is present the object is considered empty()

    This object is a drop-in replacement for Optional. If you're familiar with the Optional, class, you will be familiar with the API of this object. For Java 8 developers, this object offers a wealth of methods that only users of Java 9 and above enjoy, for example IfPresentOrElse, stream() and much more. 

       
    Nullable<String> maybeHelloWorld = Nullable.of("Hello World");

    maybeHelloWorld
          .filter("Hello World"::equals)
          .map(String::length)
          .ifPresent(value -> System.out.println(value));

    maybeHelloWorld
          .filter("Hello World"::equals)
          .map(String::length)
          .ifPresentOrElse(System.out::println,
              () -> System.out.println("Empty World"));

    maybeHelloWorld
          .map(String::length)
          .filter(s -> s <= 11)
          .orElseThrow(IllegalStateException::new);

    List<String> list = maybeHelloWorld
                          .toList();
    Author:
    Kevin H, Excelsior Software
    See Also:
    NullableDouble, NullableInt, NullableLong
